lenistic period urban site in Central Asia, Mairs explores how these ancient people lived, communicated, and understood themselves. Significant and original, The Hellenistic Far East will highlight Bactrian studies as an important part of our understanding of the ancient world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAntiquities. 0aCities and towns, AncientxAsia, Central. 0aCities and towns, AncientzAsia, Central. 0aCities and towns, Ancient. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)xAsia, Central. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zAsia, Central. 0aExcavations (Archaeology). 0aGreeksxHistoryxAsia, Central. 0aGreekszAsia, CentralxHistory. 0aGreeks. 0aGroup identityxHistoryxAsia, Central. 0aGroup identityzAsia, CentralxHistory. 0aGroup identity. 0aHellenismus. 0aSocial archaeologyxAsia, Central. 0aSocial archaeologyzAsia, Central. 0aSocial archaeology. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095954540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959545423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959545/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles